{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff (request builder -> API client). A unit test of only a helper could miss dropped labels during wiring/serialization. Higher levels rejected: System is disqualified by behavior text focusing on request content, not real network/OS effects; Agentic is disqualified because correctness does not depend on model judgment, only outbound payload fields.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub API client that records outbound payload. Call classify with a known taxonomy and assert the sent request contains the full taxonomy list (no omissions/reordering loss) before any response handling.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is response-handling across boundaries (API adapter -> normalization/validation -> public return). Stubbed invalid provider label is sufficient to trigger real failure mode. Higher levels rejected: Agentic is disqualified by behavior text \"API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy\" because we can deterministically supply that exact raw response; System is disqualified since no real network behavior is required.","test_description":"Use a stub API returning an out-of-taxonomy label (for example \"medical\"). Invoke classify and assert caller receives exactly \"unknown\" and never the raw unexpected label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior text isolates a single deterministic normalization transform; no module interaction is required to expose the failure. Higher levels rejected: Integration/System/Agentic are disqualified because the behavior explicitly fixes input as identical raw responses and checks pure normalization determinism.","test_description":"Call normalization function twice (or property-test many times) with the exact same raw API payload fixture and assert identical normalized label output each time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.0,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live API calls and checks consistency of model-produced labels; this depends on real model behavior/non-determinism. System alone is insufficient because the key risk is model decision variability, not just HTTP transport. Workflow rejected: repeated calls are repeated single-step classifications, not a multi-stage agent pipeline.","test_description":"Run N live classifications for the same document/taxonomy, logging raw provider label and final label per call. Assert final label stays constant whenever raw provider label is unchanged; any drift without raw change is failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.78,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at policy + dispatch boundary (budget logic must affect whether/how request is sent). A pure unit test could miss that enforcement is not applied before client dispatch. Higher levels rejected: System disqualified because real network is unnecessary to detect pre-dispatch enforcement; Agentic disqualified because no model output quality is involved.","test_description":"Configure a small token budget and a stub API client. Submit oversized input and assert behavior matches policy (truncate with capped payload or reject and no dispatch). Verify recorded dispatch (or lack of dispatch) reflects enforced budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.4,"Integration":0.56,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior depends on real external provider token accounting in live responses; in-process fakes can mask mismatches between local estimates and provider-reported usage. Higher level rejected: Agentic is disqualified by behavior text targeting token usage metadata, not semantic quality/classification correctness; this is real-infrastructure/API-contract validation.","test_description":"Execute live call(s) with representative document and configured budget, capture provider-reported usage fields, and assert reported total tokens are <= configured per-call budget.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is retry orchestration across classifier + API client + backoff/timer components; a stubbed 429/ratelimit signal reproduces the real failure mode. Higher levels rejected: System is disqualified because real network throttling is not required to validate retry logic; Agentic is disqualified because correctness is independent of model judgment/content.","test_description":"Stub API to return rate-limit error first, success second. Run classify with controllable clock/timer, assert module waits per retry policy, performs retry, and returns successful label instead of surfacing initial error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
